g.text: primary processingIn this step, the primary products are going different ways to the processing. Logs are transported to saw mills. For running a small sawmill 500 - 2000 m3 timber are enough and it means the producing is for the local market (bygdesag).20 000 - 80 000 m3 are necesseray for a medium sized sawmill and for a large sawmill 150 000 m3 or more are needed. In Fauske ist not that much timber at the moment and even in the future it will problably never be that much. But to implement a small sawmill is good for the area. A bigger sawmill is possible but only if logs will be imported from Sweden or Russia. The leavings of the timber harvesting and out of the saw mills can be brought to power plants which use the energy of wood to produce heat and electricity or to pulp mills. The heat can be used by the saw mills for timber drying and the overproduction of electricity is lead to the nearest by village. But the waterpower is more sufficient and produces less CO₂, thats why it doesn’t make sense to implement a power plant. The pulp mill, on the other hand, can produce sustainable packaging that can be used on a large scale in the terminal, but can also be used locally. It is also a statement that can be made to convey the image of a sustaina-ble but also very modern community. For running a pulp mill the greenfield investment is around 500 000 m3. The advantage is that lower-grade wood, production waste and paper waste of the co-sumerfs can also be used as material. Due to its slow growth, wood from Norwegian forests is very suitable as packaging material. Nevertheless, Fauske needs material from other parts of Norway to operate a pulp mill and has to import it from abroad. The best is to combine pulp mills with sawmills, so the work is better connected because it reduces the amount of energy required to manufacture the products in many areas of the production chain. Most likely outcome of small sawmill- producing for the local market - consumption of 500-2000 m3 sawlogs- products: decking, esterior cladding, logs for loghouses, wood packeging- no strenght grade timbe, possibly kiln dried timber- up to 4 jobs, multipled by the rippel effect there will be up to 8 jobsA sawmill does not necceseraly belongs to only one person. Local forest owners should join forces to make more profits, implement a strong network. Network nalysis aids identifying relations and information flow between important entities within and outside the wood value chain, thus determining drivers and barriers for adopting good solutions. Aspects other than profitability guiding ompanies’ decision processes may then be included—in particular, companies with strong local ties or in small communities may also be inclined to consider, e.g., the ocial benefits of their operations.
